				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Maybe what you are wanting to do is something like this?<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://youtu.be/0vfLNjXzNMw">http://youtu.be/0vfLNjXzNMw</a><!-- m --><br /><br />Or this<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://youtu.be/Qb99wXsS7_s">http://youtu.be/Qb99wXsS7_s</a><!-- m --><br /><br />your &quot;bank switching&quot; is an accurate term when you are dealing with games smaller than 32mbits like starfox2 and megaman X2/3 and others in an effort to make a &quot;multi game&quot; cart.<br /><br />Each address line doubles the rom in size.  So A21 <em>removed</em> from the Snes control buss, then pulled high or low manually or through a counter or like the video shows -with a micro controller, accesses the upper half of the rom or lower half.  So A21 (32mbits) is = to 2 x A20 (2 x 16mbits).   That make sense?<br /><br />I understand the desire to make your own cart.  I own every flash cart made but I wanted to learn how (and why) to make my own. It was a frustrating, hair-pulling, and gratifying project.</div>

